            "last_activity_date": 1576738300,
            "creation_date": 1576737906,
            "body": "<p>Your class violates the general contract for <code>hashCode()<\/code>, not <code>equals()<\/code>. <code>Set.contains()<\/code> uses <code>hashCode()<\/code> to achieve O(1) time.<\/p>\n\n<p>The general contract for <code>hashCode()<\/code> states that equal objects must have equal hash codes. However, in your case, <code>[v=1, w=2]<\/code> and <code>[v=2, w=1]<\/code> are considered equal, but they have different hash codes. You'd be calling <code>Objects.hash(1, 2)<\/code> and <code>Objects.hash(2, 1)<\/code> respectively.<\/p>\n\n<p>You should change your hash code implementation to make it independent of the order of <code>v<\/code> and <code>w<\/code>. One way to do this is to hash the smaller one first:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>return Objects.hash(Math.min(v, w), Math.max(v, w));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 59404488,
            "question_id": 59404356,
            "last_edit_date": 1576738300
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a1fa5ac172d7873a14e6a70e1f48fcb?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 9847991,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 7294900,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7294900/ori-marko",
                "reputation": 59316,
                "display_name": "Ori Marko",
                "accept_rate": 94
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1576738063,
            "creation_date": 1576738063,
            "body": "<p>As @Sweeper wrote, your hashCode should return same value in any parameters order, so you can return sum of parameters' hashCode:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>@Override\npublic int hashCode() {\n    return Objects.hashCode(v) + Objects.hashCode(w);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
